A total of 243 (94.2 %) patients had viral, bacterial and fungal co-infections. As shown in Fig. 1
, 9 viruses, 11 bacteria and 4 fungi were detected. 81 patients (31.5 %) had viral co-infection, 236 (91.8 %) had bacterial co-infection, and 60 (23.3 %) had fungal co-infection (Table 2
). The co-infection pathogens were as follows: S.pneumoniae (153, 59.5 %), KP (143, 55.6 %), Hi (103, 40.1 %), Aspergillus (60, 23.3 %), EBV (52, 20.2 %), E. coli (24, 9.3 %), S. aureus (21, 8.2 %), HRV (12, 4.7 %), P.aeruginosa (12, 4.7 %), MC (11, 4.3 %), HAdV (10, 3.9 %), HSV (8, 3.1 %), A. baumannii (7, 2.8 %), CP (6, 2.5 %), Mucor (6, 2.5 %), influenza B (5, 1.9 %), MP (4, 1.6 %), Bordetella pertussis (3, 1.2 %), Candida (2, 0.8 %), CMV (3, 1.2 %), influenza A (2, 0.8 %), HBoV (1, 0.4 %), HMPV (1, 0.4 %) and Cryptococcus (1, 0.4 %). The proportion of bacterial co-infection (75, 96.2 %) was highest, followed by bacterial-viral (26, 33.3 %), viral-fungal (11, 14.1 %) and viral-bacterial-fungal (11, 14.1 %) co-infections in mild category (P > 0.05; Table 2). The rates of viral co-infection (6, 35.3 %), fungal co-infection (5, 29.5 %) and bacterial-fungal co-infection (5, 29.5 %) were the highest in severe/critical category (P > 0.05; Table 2).
